No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused to request that, as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the paragraph on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned prime minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the motion to alleviate the penalties for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of an allegedly adverse contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicts is to be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the ruling as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West, the trial raised suspicions of the court's bias.
The motion to remove Section 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required to adopt it.
