"Business is based on the forward movement, so you must not emotionally bind yourself to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, to leave them again, too.
Unlike the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM’s profits involve the largest number of services, software and hardware are one-fifth each.
In 1990, hardware was still the most represented with a more than fifty percent share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-profit assets, but in the same period it invested $58 billion in purchasing promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept across the world for the first time like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson faithful, who in the midst of the great global economic crisis increased his investment.
So far, it seems that the company IBM is surviving today's crisis without damage.
