IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
She took over the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was about a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history until the 1980s. Century goes back.
They had technologies such as the famous bullet card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who was the boss of rival company Thomas J. Watson hired to help him manage the company.
This leader then even dwarfed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are based on the invincible culture and identity of the company to this day.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all possible machinery for retail - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the firm, he doubled its revenues to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for a whole forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA to direct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, to man's famous flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computing production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM is paying off over the past three years is the "Smarter Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a smart way in areas that are not even planned so far, e.g. also to improve the situation in transport and in urban administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform, which is intended to help traders direct the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
IBM founded a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia in 1932, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe Headquarters is located in Prague and here is also a top team of researchers from world level, which deals with the technology of voice recognition.
