Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the ČSSR at the time: Čedok, sports urist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and only the elect were allowed to the West at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to Lake Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the travels to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A major paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not gone by far.
The so-called. Foreign exchange commitment - the condition for a departure to the West - was only given "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most Czechs have therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dats - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad to countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that one is no longer aware of today is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the obligation to foreign exchange was lifted to the neighbouring Western European countries, which produced a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept while traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a guesthouse at that time.
A typical feature of Czechs’ trips abroad at the time was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips through charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly cheapened by air travel thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the USA, the Czechs already had currency-free payment transactions with all the highly developed countries in the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are being flied directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 thousand. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On the 17th In November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely among the most advanced countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time and for the first time in their history they gave more than 15 thousand for a single holiday stay, including the cost at the holiday destination. CZK per capita.
The Annual General Meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
Czech football has not had a chairman for almost five months and threatens that the successor to Ivan Hašek at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not be known even after the extraordinary general meeting on Thursday in Nymburk.
