Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in Ufo look, pompous pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, you can rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness is most beautiful in the water.
If Iris Meder went on a research trip for the past year and a half, one thing could not be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying back on the water, she looked high in ornately designed domes, she swam marble puttens waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bath, she recorded it in her notebook - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architectural historian Meder in this way - and now introduces them in her just published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
She led her "trip to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe" through 13 countries: in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn’t have much to do with sports, says Meder – only in the water it’s different.
It’s only annoying that swimming fans have to come to terms with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful birdsong in the park.
"I wondered one day why swimming pools always have to be so ugly," says the Meder, who lives in Vienna.
“So I started collecting beautiful baths.”
Water surface doubles architecture
Blattering in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builders have made an effort, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
“On the one hand, it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building.”
Everything visually doubles: high vaults, colorful tiles, diving boards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys something worth knowing about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkali-containing water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberé).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich roof bath, you can visit the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton looks at the snow-covered Arlberg - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can observe the goings-on on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
From three upwardly open bowls, it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal protrude into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool, the pool collector Meder got the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell like sulphur, in the Árpád bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it smells so strongly of heating oil that you hardly believe you have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline-hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to the skin as soon as you let yourself slide into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed in 1902 by the architect Dušan Jurkovic, has since been closed.
When Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
The decay, on the other hand, was countered in a charming swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already passed three phases of construction; one can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements that date from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite bath of the pool expert Iris Meder - and not only because it originated from the Black Forest.
"It's already an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
