The moved pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and deteriorated.
Now it is being reopened as an exhibition house.
When modern post-war architecture is raved about clear forms, glassy halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is an apt and famous example for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition.
Schwanzer’s pavilion at the time got the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its light and floating-looking steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well-known that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next World's Fair.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Railway Station, was rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20th. Century opened - the "20th house" was called it.
However, the building was not suitable as a museum in terms of space and technology - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new house in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, was enforced.
Husslein-Arco, a doctored in art history with a considerable career, among other things in his youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, enforced the reconstruction strongly with politicians and preservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the implementation, Krischanitz was the ideal cast.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an "enormously important place" for him, where he had looked at the exhibitions "almost every weekend."
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and ease when it was transferred to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far bigger problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy slingshot," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between the house and the road provides the exposure, a bridge leading to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tails pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema is even exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also pleased the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story."
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "arouse a real awareness".
