Smart crows spread in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": but the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others they want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities, residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals.
So far, a remedy against the "problem birds" is not in sight.
Seed crows can no longer be found out of the cities, said experts at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over Germany advised on possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the particularly protected seed crows: The use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying the traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing development and the felling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs are located in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the district had caused negative headlines.
Critics had described the catching of the animals in bird traps and the slaying with sticks as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the grievance, does nothing," the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer has noted.
Spraying nests with water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
“The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread in other places.”
Scaring is only conceivable as an exception to hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
“We have to live with them, we can’t get them away.”
Without the surrounding area, the problem in the cities could not be solved, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of the animals from sensitive living areas and lure-offers is conceivable in order to resettle them in other places.
"Info boards instead of chainsaws" advertised the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens for a completely different handling of the animals: "After all, we can best bear a pimple in the face".
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberg crow teaching trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: seed crows not only use aids to get a treat, but also produce their tools themselves as a tool.
Behavioral scientists at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to collapse a scaffold with stones in order to get to a moth larva.
Without much training, they purposefully realized what size and shape a stone must have to make the platform collapse.
In a second attempt, the smart crows then had to solve a trickier problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid pieces of wire for them.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle out of the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded immediately.
