Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their level of education, attitude towards violence and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a fairly new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more sensible, democratic and less violent than those who remain sitting behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends like in "likes," text news and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content a day, Facebook's "Datasupernova" is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with the name of that page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you don't normally reach with your clipboard on the road.
“If you used to try to question people from the British National Party, it was very hard to identify them.”
"They first had to inform the party and they would never have allowed them access," says Bartlett.
“On Facebook, all this falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site provides a way to detect and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues have found that students who discussed their full-on rush on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent on this issue.
Moreno suggests that equal students, for example residential counselors, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and head of the Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle told the Washington Post.
“We found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise.”
Facebook is also constantly tapping the data of its own population.
The page's data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Fortune Index (using primarily information that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data discovery pit available to others for research purposes.)
But the users of Facebook know that the page is watching them, whether they want to or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to apply your own personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles at all," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
“As for her, it was all about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant will be absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information is true in a user profile and in posts.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people," he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still happening offline.”
