For someone who is known for abhorring in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to light when he reacts seemingly impatiently to Cringely's questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to topics or side stories of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems somehow eerily far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and his own vision for the future of the computer.
