Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could build for $15. That was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are slackening:
Long before he resurrected Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their shares.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, so what?”
You own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [it's such people] who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
This happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if that could have been Microsoft of the 1990s...
They caught the defeat from the win.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about your intricacies.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it boils down to taste, it boils down to trying to deal with the best stuff people have created and then try to bring these things together to what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
