How to Unmask a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy meeting the accusations of sexual harassment on the part of several women. The two sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State's management is accused of perjury as one allegedly withheld reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy claimed to American President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself as he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of the violations in campaign funding, which is related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating at school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam responses so that they themselves stood up well in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception are we experiencing?
As studies show, we lie between 10 and 200 times every day.
However, many of these lies are considered emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
To recognize lies or “Uncovering lies” is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a board game such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Hab dich!", revealing a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out extensive research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They do not always stutter, stammer, blush and fidget.
From this, however, one must not conclude that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
A skilled lying defuser can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of exposure. And it is clear that unmasking a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find our way around our complex world, especially if hiring or questioning people or negotiations or administration are among one’s own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, arousing their interest and mastering their own emotions. And they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverts are more likely to lie than introverts, that men are more likely to label "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "oriented to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when one person has been exposed as a culprit, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing this person’s normal behavior.
This is called "baselining," the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the later evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
