Climate adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and stoked high hopes regarding economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of the climatic adversity, there can be no talk of growth, but on the contrary, the most important economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in the millions in agriculture, but also set tight limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter, which is mainly due to the historical reduction of agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a braking effect on other economic sectors.
According to one from the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (dt. Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) report on the effects of the frost was damaged to 582 000 hectares of agricultural lands, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed. Above all, the cultivation of vegetables, corn and chickpea was affected.
The decline in economic activity by November has caused unemployment to rise continuously in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa. This is 18 969 more people than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
“What we are currently observing is a rise in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses in the market as a result of the cuts in funding from the legislation passed to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are banned from accumulating dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for anything else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people leaving the country looking for work abroad, particularly in the United States, has declined. This is due, on the one hand, to the entry problems and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work here, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of undeclared work. According to INEGI, this comprises 60.38 percent of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institution) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Governmental Employment and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September; that is very much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decline in ADI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and growing unemployment, the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $630 $597 from January to June, representing a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the $5 143 312 in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) in turn recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies from the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos, which were to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The Land Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be found until November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship, the first year of government Mario López Valdés made clear incapacity for government.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), held that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
“The economic activity in Sinaloa was really poor this year. Hard work needs to be done to regain the terrain lost this year and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the government team, which has already been well-attuned, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López expressed that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed.
“The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently in motion to create economic dynamics that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will conclude the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefining a vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (American Association of Mexico) in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to do more dynamic productive activities.
“In general, we have observed that work was being done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program for the redefinition of the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that steers the government's efforts in better directions.
“In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
“There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he expressed.
