The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its twenty-year existence
“Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that will come true”
In the exclusive conversation with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They were expected to spend more than 20 years, but the band assures that a dream will come true for them when they play in Costa Rica.
That was assured by the group's bassist and co-founder, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica from 19.30.
You read an excerpt from the conversation, the complete copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream come true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that will also be realized for us.
This is just the second time we've been playing in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It's such a beautiful country that we'll definitely stay there for a few more days.
It's exciting for us to get our music there.
I ask you this because the band's fans are totally devoted. You will experience the days before the concert intensively.
What do you think of your most avid fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've had in the last 21 years have taken place over the past two weeks.
We played at a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we feel like playing there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are excited about the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you meet Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua to surf. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. This way, about people who love surfing, we've learned about it.
With a view of the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we set no boundaries.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from every album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we will play is not easy.
When we include two or three songs that we haven’t played in a long time in the repertoire, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they could be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I believe that none of us imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years. It seems like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited about bringing out music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
From time to time, a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and are honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on her tour. We are happy to still be friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this arisen Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual for a band like yours to stay with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. This alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky to still be alive and besides, we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship with glory has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds that love your music.
As long as you think that people have come because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has launched without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We never cared about that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who set up the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think of what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and therefore chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band best. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. I'm sure it'll be exciting.
Why do you change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter whenever you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to mind.
Who did you become a bassist influenced by?
From so many+
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I can think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that’s great, because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first, her music was darker, now it's more positive.
Why?
That's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the new album that could seem a bit frivolous. But there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
To both of them came the tears when I heard Ed playing them. They are very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - e.g. when you lose a family member or a friend - that will affect your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
Peru:
Fujimori came to the hospital again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his GP informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for violating human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several conditions, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on and under control four times.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body members.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish this because he thought he was innocent.
He has undergone surgery on tongue cancer four times and he has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía detention centre since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly operating during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official secondment, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will launch its visit from Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. That, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the culmination of his fully booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information about all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica sought Calderón's support for the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community. This statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and industrialized countries, since November. Since January this year, an agreement has been in place on the exchange of tax information to avoid double investment with the South American country.
The Uruguayan government has sought in recent years to speed up the concretization of agreements on tax information exchanges in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). This is what countries are concerned that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement has been in place between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The mustached installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game, which comes to the store counters of all the world this month, has been tailored from the beginning to the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable console, which can be used to play three-dimensionally without any special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to say how the stereoscopy works without glasses," assured Omar Álvarez, the person in charge of the press specializing in Nintendo in Spain at the launch of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez declared that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game of Nintendo to be developed for this console from the beginning" because until now, successful articles such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" have been adaptations of already existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesperson underlined that, although it was three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows for a fast, fluid game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" included two games in one: the first part is "easy" to capture the less chevered users.
After that, the experts can turn a "second round" about the different game levels, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, in order to overcome the obstacles without becoming victims of the "optical effects", it must always be played three-dimensionally.
This excursion Super Marios into the three-dimensional world also means the return of the figure to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success of the last editions: The mustache-bearded installer must overcome platforms peppered with danger to free the Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news in the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom vouches for Portillo's delivery to the United States
Guatemala's president, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would grant the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo so that he would be responsible for the $70 million conspiracy to launder money in the United States.
Thus, the trial over the U.S. request for extradition from Portillo ends so that it can be brought to justice there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed his decision based on the independence of judicial authority and government, taking into account that a decision-making court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his government he had not interfered in court decisions and had granted all extradition requests he was informed of.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom’s action is an act of government that takes place when all judicial and constitutional bodies are exhausted to convict the former president of the state (2000 -2004).
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited when his legal situation in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for embezzling 120 million quetzales at the Defense Department during his reign. This trial preceded the extradition, but the minister lodged an objection and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people threatened by social exclusion
The organization was launched to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organisation Trinijove have produced important results: in this quarter of a century, 6000 young people threatened by social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people took part, took stock yesterday.
Trinijove was launched in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems that were at risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous responsible persons of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association during these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions during election campaign times demonstrated the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green councillor Ricard Goma took part in the celebrations.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Sparkasse La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was launched in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated. But he added that the work done so far is "a good foundation."
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a role model who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in trouble.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it does," he explained.
Occupied house where giant parties were hosted was cleared
The homeowners had 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on the street Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona) occupied.
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 have come to an end on the street Balmes.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building at noon yesterday, which they had illegally occupied and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair. The eviction was carried out on judicial order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be controlled," the property manager confirmed.
The squatters, who had occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical facility and part of the water supply with them. In addition, they had painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans with alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors, huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also sustained damage from it.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that her business would have declined by 80% since the start of the house occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters made their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks at three euros, while these cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure restaurant had been reported by the neighbors for disturbing the rest, while according to her statement the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters and in particular from the guests of the festivals, which were organized there, and which, according to the statements of the disgruntled neighbors, became more and more and longer in recent weeks.
The person in charge of the discotheque explained that the harassment had been so great that it agreed with the owner of the building not having to pay rent for the past nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that it had received more complaints from the neighbours in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had last week called for the building to be cleared immediately and to get to grips with the problems of civil coexistence as well as the coming down of the district.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that the squatters had penetrated into all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments in recent months. In some, thefts had even occurred.
With that in mind, he added that "it was necessary to put an end to impunity and crack down on the anti-social acts in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris neighbourhood was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 15.30, the police approached the street Montral No. 35, after receiving a call from a neighbor who had watched four people want to enter the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The municipal tender for the 16 gates opens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its rebuke on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
He was even compared in numbers to New York's Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park became the upper limit of Barcelona again in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is among the few that does not spread in the north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park plays with this idea.
Central Park no longer served as a model, but Yellowstone with wild boar in the role of the yogi bear.
So far was when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate points to the concept of a park.
Either that's the case, or someone is going to put gates on the countryside.
The question arises by itself: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for proposals is not only the topic of discussion in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona, but also from an organizational point of view, but also with regard to a reflection on the city.
It is almost a recurrent topic that two members of this old-established caste, who meet in the elevator, can fall back on.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the material for one of the rare correspondences between what three architects from Barcelona think about it, and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The call for proposals is appropriate.
For Roldán "it is necessary" to talk about the "front on the mountain" after the attack on the coast, as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, who has not been played out over the green apples.
“One should start from the principle that Barcelona’s largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," judges the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" holds a "lexical trap" in itself: one must not "imagine it as accesses to a park, but as a limitation of areas on which to act."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, considers the proposal an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers."
Dangers as a result of the "uncertainty that the design of a public space entails today" after the experiences from the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the field of the forum.
The first fear is the own limitation to what may be built.
"To narrow down something always means to define the next step," i.e. to cross it.
“One has to think about new urban planning instruments, because the present [referring to the plan General Metropolitano (PGM)] can lead to a real catastrophe.”
Modol, who adheres more closely to the question, says that the side of Collserola, which is heading towards Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that is not heading towards Barcelona," for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronate de Collserola that should not "fall on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
He also notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the escort letter that allows the architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams launched ("just the right thing," he says, "We architects should just be a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the headline of this article is complex, since a global view of Collserola is lacking in the tendering conditions: "There were 16 competitions in cross-section," he says, "on the mountain sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that the area considers in its entirety."
That, at least in his case, has led him to participate in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would conflict with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip is equipped directly above the Ronda de Dalt in its entire length in such a way that a soft transition between the city and green zones is created.
