Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announces details of the plane crash that killed the government secretary Francisco Blake and another seven people.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the investigation results of the accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people died, indicate that the helicopter with all its intact structure has hit the ground directly without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before takeoff that the weather conditions were suitable for flight.
“The fact that the propeller wings had contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts.”
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for transporting the staff.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had come down.
“In the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the mark-up affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an obliquene of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Relief Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Estado Mayor Presidencial at a cruising speed during the impact and the aircraft had fallen on a soft slope.
“This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact.”
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In line with flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight. This means that the crew would have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the start. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico state, some low-hanging clouds rose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter match. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight path before the impact.
Scattering of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available up to this point indicates that the helicopter had bounced from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggest that the helicopter had hit the ground with its unscathed structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the scene of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest results indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is sloping and has an obliquene of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a meticulous search on an area that went beyond the cordoned-off area at the scene of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the unscathed aircraft structure had bounced against the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Mexican Social Security Institution is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institution of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence," which aims to use the genetic markers to be found in connection with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (department of medical research, focus on biochemistry) at the Clinic Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate degree program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where every Saturday from 8.00 am tests with children and young people are carried out.
He stressed that the investigation began on the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (in the west of the state of México) and since the 8th. October will continue on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study is to get to know the factors and role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents in the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the worldwide day of diabetes, he stated that it is intended that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should fill out nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and under the supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of illness to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also stated that on the aforementioned Saturdays, the subjects measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of the concern of health workers about the alarming weight gain of young people.
“The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 found that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. The overweightness has also increased dramatically," emphasized the specialist of the IMSS.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that a Mexican (in) is on average 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of the energy (calories) taken to us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
