The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs emanating from the pavement, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes if the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assured that if the laying out and maintenance of the asphalt flooring is reduced.
In his lecture "Potholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which, however, has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic tough-elastic behavior.
Tough-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120° C. it is very viscous and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ's researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority flexible road surface, which is composed of six layers of material, the last of which included asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers lies a layer of wear made of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer, had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called supporting layer, which is made of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
The fact that this road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also requires an appropriate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates into the layer and only escapes again with difficulty. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research works were still awaited, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are even already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without application of high temperatures.
