Thus was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopeist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last 4. November, a lophoscopist of the Prosecutor's Office (CTI) investigative unit from Cali entered as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopeists in the CTI's department, Eliazar González had on-call duty this week, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he frequently had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he settled over to Valle and after the completion of the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin, which is exposed to frictions, i.e. the hand and foot surfaces.
In the week of use against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of the man who had run the oldest guerrilla in the world could be. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger imprint sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name) with him.
However, when he reached the place where the body was located with the examination, he could not identify it because of his physical appearance, because this did not resemble the pictures he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer of the area, was not wearing glasses and was very much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting trowel and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the print sheet.
He had seen right: it was "Alfonso Cano."
The same night, this Puerto Tejada-born man was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that it was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the appreciation that the President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González gave at a press conference about the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopes not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many criminals present false identification papers or they have none.
We'll take their fingerprints and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in the event of a theft, because the thief had leaned on his hand at exactly this point when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
“Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting. But in this case, we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had taken part in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or burdened.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
When the investigation was suspected that a family member could be suspect, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that this is the murderer, it is nevertheless linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A Dactyloskopist of the CTI explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a planting trowel or ribbon is used to take away.
After that, the imprints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil registry office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification papers," explained the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything was as it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything is gold that shines, not all you touch is a fingerprint.
However, it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
