"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers, who are numerously represented in Lubmin, with regard to the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 m.
During their construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be dodged.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream, said.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long queue of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was provided off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from it, as the Swedes were not eager to see a Russian state company permanently settled at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas located in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be little likely, since the sweat seams were estimated to be at a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas transmission line.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures one meter in diameter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of locomotion through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the line management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies are E. ON and BASF affiliated (each to 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group of companies GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transported amount of gas is," Jens Müller said.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour cost should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
